<br>
What I have seen so far suggests that most bomb casualties were as a result of heat, blast, exposure to intense gamma and neutron radiation and, to a lesser extent, exposure to short lived fallout products in the immediate aftermath of the explosion (The first 100 hours). What proportion of this would be from short-lived FP’s and what would be from neutron-induced radioactivity in the dust etc I don’t know, <br>
<br>
However I have lifted this unexpected quote from a Japan based Hiroshima website.<br>
<br>
“Fortunately it has not been observed that the long term effects of radiation affected A-bomb survivors nor that a radiation exposure caused genetic damages.”<br>
<br>
So far this seems to support my (admittedly controversial and somewhat counterintuitive) hypothesis that, in the great scheme of things, a GCNR crash in a populated area is not going to be a significantly greater catastrophe than the crash of a conventional rocket of similar payload capacity.<br>
<br>
Indeed, I still think it could be a lot less, by definition, the more FP’s; the less hydrogen fuel will be left on board. Indeed at launch the GCNR mooted (I shall continue to use liberty ship as an example, not because I am arguing that it would work, but because it is convenient to refer to) has only just over 1000 tons of pure hydrogen on board with no oxidiser present. A FAO (Failure to achieve orbit) crash may mean that only 500 tons is present, with a botched landing there would be even less. <br>
<br>
Whilst this would cause a big fire, the main destructive effect would be the impact of the dead weight of the rocket and its components combined with the release of the gaseous fission fragments. By contrast a Super-Sea-Dragon could conceivably crash with 20,000 tons upwards of fuel/oxidiser mix on board. This would cause a colossal explosion and completely destroy any but the largest of cities.<br>
<br>
Sure a GCNR crash would kill a lot of people, and I have no reason to believe that a significant proportion would not be from radiation sickness from exposure to the intense shorter lived FP’s however I think it is highly likely that the overall casualties would be a good bit less than for a crash of a chemical rocket of similar capacity.<br>
<br>
As I asked before, Are we saying that being blown to bits or burned to death is OK but radiation sickness is not? <br>
<br>
